Fantasy Football Analysis

Analysis Questions

Part 1

  • Is there a correlation between fantasy points and wins?

  • Is there a correlation between fantasy points and team points scored?

  • Is there a correlation between team points allowed and fantasy points scored by position?

Part 2

  • Which QB statistics have the highest correlation to fantasy points?

  • Which RB statistics have the highest correlation to fantasy points?

  • Which WR/TE statistics have the highest correlation to fantasy points?

Rules of Fantasy Football

Summary of how fantasy football works

People draft teams from a pool of real NFL players. Points are gained on a weekly basis depending on how players perform. For this project I chose to use Draft Kings scoring system because it is the most popular and is considered the standard system.

Point System:

Passing:

  • Touchdown = 4points

  • Yard = 0.04 points

    Running:

  • Touchdown = 6 points

  • Yard = 0.1 points

    Receiving:

  • Touchdown = 6 points

  • Yard = 0.1 points

  • Catch = 1 points

    Fantasy team consist of quarterbacks, running backs, and wide receivers. In this project I tested the strength of the relationships between different statistics and fantasy points. We want to find which fantasy football stats matter the most and which calculated stats might also relate to fantasy points. We also can sum up the fantasy points for all the NFL teams to find out if fantasy football success relates to actual team success. There will be 2 parts to this project. Part 1 is team based stats and part 2 is a more specific dive into stats by position group.

    For more details read the links below:

  • https://www.nfl.com/news/how-to-play-fantasy-football-a-beginner-s-guide-0ap3000000692955

  • https://www.nola.com/sports/betting/fantasy/article_61d50a44-0528-11ec-892d-0f47623dbc0d.html

Organize Data with SQL:

  • Next I use SQL to organize the data and combine data sets using the ‘team’ column for a left join.

  • This will allow me to compare team records and points to fantasy points.

Fantasy_PTS_By_Team = sqldf("select team, sum(Total_DKP)
                            from df 
                            group by team")
Fantasy_PTS_By_Team = rename(Fantasy_PTS_By_Team, 'Total_DKP' = 'sum(Total_DKP)')
Combined_Team_Stats = sqldf("select team_records.team, team_records.wins, 
                            team_records.losses, team_records.ties, team_records.points_for,                               team_records.points_against, Fantasy_PTS_By_Team.Total_DKP
                            from team_records
                            left join Fantasy_PTS_By_Team on 
                            team_records.team = Fantasy_PTS_By_Team.team")
Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team = sqldf("select Opponent_abbrev, sum(Total_DKP)
                                 from df 
                                 group by Opponent_abbrev")
Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team = rename(Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team, 'Total_DKP' = 'sum(Total_DKP)')
Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team = rename(Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team, 'team' = 'Opponent_abbrev')
Combined_Points_Against = sqldf("select team_records.team, team_records.wins, 
                                team_records.losses, team_records.ties, team_records.points_for                                 , team_records.points_against, Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team                                        .Total_DKP
                                from team_records
                                left join Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team on team_records.team =                                      Fantasy_PTS_Against_Team.team")

Now Compare Opponents Defense to Fantasy Points by Position:

  • Now I am going to compare how the opponents defense affects fantasy points by position

  • I will do this by extracting the 5 best and 5 worst fantasy defenses and seeing how many points were scored against them on average by position group.

worst_teams = team_records[order(points_against),]
bottom_ten = tail(worst_teams, 5)
bottom_ten_teams = bottom_ten$team
bottom_ten_teams_df = as.data.frame(bottom_ten_teams)
Vs_bottom_ten = sqldf("select df.pos, df.pass_att, df.rush_att, df.rec, df.team, df                                     .Opponent_abbrev, df.Total_DKP, bottom_ten_teams_df.bottom_ten_teams
                         from df 
                         left join bottom_ten_teams_df on df.Opponent_abbrev =                                          bottom_ten_teams_df.bottom_ten_teams")
Vs_bottom_ten = Vs_bottom_ten[complete.cases(Vs_bottom_ten),]

QB_vs_bottom_ten = sqldf("select pos, avg(Total_DKP) 
                         from Vs_bottom_ten
                         where pass_att >= 10 and pos = 'QB'")
RB_vs_bottom_ten = sqldf("select pos, avg(Total_DKP) 
                         from Vs_bottom_ten
                         where rush_att >= 5 and pos = 'RB'")
WR_TE_vs_bottom_ten = sqldf("select pos, avg(Total_DKP) 
                         from Vs_bottom_ten
                         where rec >= 3 and pos ='WR' or pos ='TE'")

top_ten = head(worst_teams, 5)
top_ten_teams = top_ten$team
top_ten_teams_df = as.data.frame(top_ten_teams)
Vs_top_ten = sqldf("select df.pos, df.team, df.Opponent_abbrev, df.pass_att, df.rush_att, df                            .rec, df.Total_DKP, top_ten_teams_df.top_ten_teams
                         from df 
                         left join top_ten_teams_df on df.Opponent_abbrev = top_ten_teams_df                            .top_ten_teams")
Vs_top_ten = Vs_top_ten[complete.cases(Vs_top_ten),]
QB_vs_top_ten = sqldf("select pos, avg(Total_DKP) 
                         from Vs_top_ten
                         where pass_att >= 10 and pos = 'QB'")
RB_vs_top_ten = sqldf("select pos, avg(Total_DKP) 
                         from Vs_top_ten
                         where rush_att >= 5 and pos = 'RB'")
WR_TE_vs_top_ten = sqldf("select pos, avg(Total_DKP) 
                         from Vs_top_ten
                         where rec >= 3 and pos ='WR' or pos ='TE'")

Vs_Top_Teams = c(QB_vs_top_ten$`avg(Total_DKP)`, RB_vs_top_ten$`avg(Total_DKP)`, WR_TE_vs_top_ten$`avg(Total_DKP)`)
Vs_Worst_Teams = c(QB_vs_bottom_ten$`avg(Total_DKP)`, RB_vs_bottom_ten$`avg(Total_DKP)`, WR_TE_vs_bottom_ten$`avg(Total_DKP)`)
row_names4 = c("QB Fantasy Points", "RB Fantasy Points", "WR/TE Fantasy Points")
positional_top_table = as.data.frame(Vs_Top_Teams,row_names4)
positional_worst_table = as.data.frame(Vs_Worst_Teams, row_names4)

Part 1 conclusion:

  • Fantasy points does relate to wins but has a stronger relationship to points scored than wins.

  • On average, players do put up more fantasy points when playing against bottom 5 teams vs top 5 teams as far as points allowed.

  • There is a correlation between team success and fantasy points.

Next I will organize the data by position starting with QB and Begin Part 2:

QB_df1 <- sqldf("select pos, player, team, pass_cmp, pass_att, pass_yds, pass_td, pass_int,                 pass_sacked, pass_sacked_yds, pass_long, pass_rating, comb_pass_rush_play,                     rush_scrambles, comb_pass_play, comb_rush_play, pass_poor_throws, pass_blitzed,                pass_hurried, Total_DKP 
             from df
             where pos = 'QB' and pass_att > 15")
QB_totals = sqldf("select pos, player, team, avg(pass_cmp), avg(pass_att), avg(pass_yds), 
                 avg (pass_td), avg(pass_int), avg(pass_sacked), avg(pass_long), 
                 avg(pass_rating), avg(rush_scrambles), avg(comb_pass_play), 
                 avg(comb_rush_play), avg(pass_poor_throws), avg(pass_blitzed), 
                 avg(pass_hurried), avg(Total_DKP) 
                 from QB_df1
                 group by player")

  • pass_att must be greater than 15 because we are trying to exclude QB’s who were subbed into the end of a game that was a blowout.

  • They will be automatic outliers and will skew the data.

Next I will Create a Function to Calculate Correlation Quicker:

corr <- function(x,y)
  cor.test(x,y,method='pearson')

Next I will Find the Correlation Between Each Statistic and Fantasy Points and Create a Table:

cor_avg_cmp = corr(QB_totals$AVG_Cmp,QB_totals$AVG_Total_DKP)

Part 2 Conclusion:

When selecting a fantasy team:

At QB use:

  • y = 7.2347x + 6.9655 where x is the number of passing touchdowns.

  • This is the model that is most likely to give an accurate estimate.

  • To have an extra advantage on your opponents you can use y = 0.2676x -6.6782, where x is passer rating

At RB, the most reliable model is:

  • y = 0.2178x + 0.8626, where x is rushing yards

  • For an extra advantage you should look for physical runners who gain a lot of yards after contact

  • To predict their points you can use y = 0.3664x + 3.0762 where x is yards after contact

For WR and TE the best prediction model is:

  • y = 0.1997x + 1.2864 where x is receiving yards.

  • It is also important to look at how much their QB likes them using y = 2.7073x - 0.0067 where x is the number of targets.

Overall this project should help fantasy players look for which specific stats can help them select players who will put up good fantasy points in the future.
